WEBVTT

00:05.940 --> 00:15.280
Oh, dear colleagues, ladies and gentlemen, I'm honored to be here today to co-chair the

00:15.280 --> 00:20.160
third United Nations Food Systems Summit with Prime Minister Abiy, thank you very much,

00:20.780 --> 00:26.160
whom I thank once again for his hospitality and for his friendship.

00:26.160 --> 00:34.740
This is the first time that this summit is being held in Africa. We choose to co-organize

00:34.740 --> 00:42.200
this event in Addis Abeba with the Ethiopian government, not only because Italy has a special

00:42.200 --> 00:48.380
relation with Ethiopia and a pragmatic cooperation based on concrete projects and initiatives,

00:49.200 --> 00:55.860
but also because we believe it is essential to involve the African continent as a

00:55.860 --> 01:02.920
protagonist in the choices and actions of the international community, starting, of course,

01:03.080 --> 01:09.840
with the momentous challenge that is the subject of our work today, which is food security.

01:10.940 --> 01:18.500
This is a top priority challenge as demonstrated by the broad and qualified participation in

01:18.500 --> 01:25.960
the summit and the presence of UN Deputy Secretary General Mohammed, whom I greet and thank.

01:27.140 --> 01:34.360
Although it has drastically decreased over the last 70 years, global food insecurity

01:34.360 --> 01:42.760
still affects around 10% of the world's population, and this percentage is largely concentrated

01:42.760 --> 01:52.000
here in Africa, where one in five people suffer from hunger and do not have access to sufficient,

01:52.140 --> 02:00.720
safe and nutritious food to lead a healthy life. This situation, already complex, has

02:00.720 --> 02:08.080
been exacerbated by the crisis the world is currently facing. While we were working to

02:08.080 --> 02:14.320
overcome the shock of the pandemic, we had to deal with Russia's war of aggression against

02:14.320 --> 02:22.720
Ukraine, which disrupted economic and trade flows and processes, destabilised energy markets

02:22.720 --> 02:29.600
and fuelled waves of inflation that hit the most fragile nations, especially in the global

02:29.600 --> 02:38.580
South and in Africa. And we know very well that when people do not have access to sufficient

02:38.580 --> 02:47.500
food or lose the means to produce it, the consequences can be catastrophic. Poverty worsens,

02:47.900 --> 02:55.400
conflicts intensify and communities become more vulnerable to violence, terrorism or

02:55.400 --> 03:02.540
forced migration. Food insecurity is therefore in its every aspect a political issue, but

03:02.540 --> 03:09.420
not only. It is also, above all, an economic issue. We would be making a serious mistake

03:09.880 --> 03:17.160
if we limited ourselves to looking at food systems through the face of poverty, suffering

03:17.160 --> 03:24.920
and hunger. Food systems are an engine of growth and development, both for the most

03:24.920 --> 03:31.760
fragile nations and for those that are economically more solid. At the heart of our action there

03:31.760 --> 03:37.960
must therefore be the development for the communities where we choose to focus our efforts

03:37.960 --> 03:46.400
on. And it is not enough to help those communities to produce the food needed to feed the population,

03:47.120 --> 03:53.640
but it is also necessary for that food to be marketed, to have access to markets with

03:53.640 --> 03:59.500
solid and resilient production and distribution chance. This is the only way we can enable

03:59.500 --> 04:05.640
a community to prosper with the resources it possesses, generating employment and stable

04:05.640 --> 04:12.720
lasting growth. This is Italy's point of view, and it is the red line that links the initiatives

04:12.720 --> 04:18.760
and projects of the Matei Plan for Africa, starting of course with the agri-food sector,

04:18.940 --> 04:26.820
an area in which Italy can boast unique know-how that combines tradition and innovation.

04:27.700 --> 04:34.880
We have made this heritage available for our African partners, and together with them we

04:34.880 --> 04:39.860
have built public-private partnerships that attract investments and guarantee concrete

04:39.860 --> 04:46.600
results. We are successfully testing this in Algeria, where we are working to reclaim

04:46.600 --> 04:57.760
over 36,000 hectares of desert to produce up to 45,000 tons of additional cereals and

04:57.760 --> 05:05.800
legumes per year, creating 6,000 jobs and generating benefits for over 600,000 people.

05:06.600 --> 05:14.220
This endeavor is also underway in Senegal, Ghana and Congo, and aims to soon involve

05:14.220 --> 05:22.320
Podiwar and Presidente Ruto Kenia. Our blueprint is also working in Tunisia, where we are strengthening

05:22.320 --> 05:28.120
capacities and skills for the use of water, a resource around which there will be an increasing

05:28.120 --> 05:34.920
geopolitical and sovereignty challenge. But we have chosen to apply this vision to other

05:34.920 --> 05:40.960
projects as well, such as the one developed together with the European Union's Global

05:40.960 --> 05:47.460
Gateway, which combines European financial resources and private capital to support the

05:47.460 --> 05:53.600
development of coffee production chains in various African nations. And then there is,

05:53.600 --> 05:59.620
of course, the centrality of the technical and scientific training, which is crucial to

05:59.620 --> 06:05.500
make a difference and must be integrated into a supply chain approach, from seed to production

06:05.500 --> 06:12.620
to product distribution. In this context, just a few days ago, we signed an agreement

06:12.620 --> 06:19.280
for the establishment of a professional agricultural training center in Algeria, which will serve

06:19.280 --> 06:26.140
as a reference point for the Sahel and the whole of Africa. Our goal, we have stated

06:26.140 --> 06:35.480
this on many occasions, is not to create dependency, but to support self-reliance. This goal also

06:35.500 --> 06:43.260
involves what we usually refer to as food sovereignty, the right of people to shape its

06:43.260 --> 06:51.040
own production model based on their identity. Food sovereignty means not going along with

06:51.040 --> 06:58.660
the standardization of food production, which lowers quality and concentrates wealth, but

06:58.660 --> 07:06.400
instead investing in promoting local high-quality products. Small and medium-sized farmers and

07:06.400 --> 07:14.320
their families are the backbone of agricultural and environmental systems. They are the primary

07:14.320 --> 07:21.320
guardians of the land and must be given the means to live with dignity and with a fair

07:21.320 --> 07:27.960
recognition of their work. And this is why Italy, with its network of institutions, businesses,

07:27.960 --> 07:35.780
and protection consortia, is ready to do its part to promote the export of African geographical

07:36.060 --> 07:42.900
indication to European and global markets by building promotion and distribution networks.

07:44.220 --> 07:53.000
So dear Deputy Secretary Muhammad, dear Prime Minister, dear colleagues, Cicero, one of the

07:53.000 --> 08:01.120
most important philosophers of ancient Rome, said that of all the arts from which some

08:01.120 --> 08:11.080
profit is gained, none is better than agriculture, none more profitable, none sweeter, none more

08:11.080 --> 08:20.020
worthy of a man and of a free man. Thousands of years later, this teaching is still valid

08:20.020 --> 08:29.180
and shows us the way forward. Food is a right, a cultural expression, the pillar of a nation's

08:29.180 --> 08:36.220
identity and sovereignty. But it is also the first step towards being truly free, independent,

08:36.680 --> 08:39.760
and masters of our own destiny. I thank you.

